    <h1>task</h1>

      <div onclick='document.location="/release/0.5/task-0.5.tar.gz"; return false;' class="linked"
           style="-moz-border-radius: 15px;
                  -webkit-border-bottom: 15px;
                   padding: 25px;
                   margin: 30px;
                   border: 4px solid #000;
                   background: #2C77C1;
                   color: #fff;
                   font-size: 3em;
                   float: right;
                    ">
          Version 0.5
      </div>

    <p>
        Task is a simple management cli for tracking tasks.
    </p>

    <p>
        This interface wraps a file using the simplest possible format
        where each task is represented as a single line of text in
        the file.
    </p>

    <p>
        Each task has an id of its line number in the file.
    </p>

    <p>
        Task ids are ephemeral, so as tasks are completed, added or
        prioritised the id will change. The id is primarily for interactive
        use.
    </p>

    <h2>quick start</h2>

    <p>
      Here are the basic operation you can perform with task. These examples use long form commands,
      however you can replace any long form command with its first letter, i.e. l is equivalent to list,
      n is equivalent to new:
    </p>

    <p>
    specify a custom task file:
    </p>
    <pre>
    $ TASK_FILE=~/.task task
    </pre>
    <p>
    list all tasks:
    </p>
    <pre>
    $ task
    </pre>

    <p>
      search in list of tasks:
    </p>
    <pre>
    $ task list searchterm
    </pre>

    <p>complete task at top of stack:</p>
    <pre>
    $ task mark
    </pre>

    <p>complete a specific task:</p>
    <pre>
    $ task mark 2
    </pre>

    <p>create task:</p>
    <pre>
    $ task new This is an item in my task list.
    </pre>

    <p>order tasks in editor:</p>
    <pre>
    $ task order
    </pre>

    <p>order tasks in specific editor:</p>
    <pre>
    $ EDITOR=emacs task order
    </pre>

    <p>move a task to the top of the stack:</p>
    <pre>
    task prioritise task-id
    </pre>

    <p>list all complete tasks:</p>
    <pre>
    task history
    </pre>

    <p>search in list of complete tasks:</p>
    <pre>
    task history searchterm
    </pre>

    <h2>installation</h2>
    
    <p>
      Task is a single shell script. Just put it on your path and you are done.
    </p>

    <p>
      It is also a standard practice to utilise two aliases for task. One 
      representing a task file in your current directory, and one representing 
      a global task file in your home directory. The current convention for 
      these aliases is `x` for the local instance of task, and `xx` for the 
      global instance of task.
    </p>

    <pre>
    alias x=task    
    alias xx="TASK_FILE=$HOME/.task x"
    </pre>

